    <!-- HOW IT WORKS -->
    <section class="mechanism">
      <h2>How Lion's Mane Works</h2>
      <p class="mechanism-intro">Most nootropics give you a temporary lift. Lion's Mane works at a structural level, supporting the systems that determine how well your brain and body perform over time.</p>

      <div class="mechanism-card">
        <div class="mechanism-points">
          <div class="point">
            <h4><span class="point-num">1.</span>Supports Nerve Growth Factor (NGF).</h4>
            <p>Lion's Mane is one of the few natural compounds known to support the body's production of Nerve Growth Factor, the protein your brain uses to keep neurons growing, connected, and healthy. Its active compounds, hericenones and erinacines, have been studied for this effect for decades.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="point">
            <h4><span class="point-num">2.</span>Promotes neurogenesis and neural plasticity.</h4>
            <p>Lion's Mane plays a role in the formation of new neurons and the connections between them. Together, these are the biological foundation of how your brain learns, adapts, and stores memory.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="point">
            <h4><span class="point-num">3.</span>Helps combat oxidative stress.</h4>
            <p>The fruiting body contains antioxidant compounds that help neutralize the kind of daily free-radical damage that accumulates in nerve cells and contributes to cognitive aging.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="point">
            <h4><span class="point-num">4.</span>Nourishes the gut-brain axis.</h4>
            <p>Lion's Mane acts as a prebiotic for beneficial gut bacteria, which produce neurotransmitters and short-chain fatty acids that influence mood and cognition. What's good for your gut is often good for your brain.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="mechanism-footnote">Summarized from published research on <em>Hericium erinaceus</em> and neurological function.</p>
    </section>

